The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, August 25, 2004  Corporate Briefs																								 Nelco Ltd, a Tata group company, plans to double its authorised capital base to Rs 50 crore from Rs 25 crore through equity and preference shares. The board has passed a resolution to this effect. The enhanced authorised capital would comprise 2.50 crore shares of Rs 10 each and 25 lakh redeemable preference shares of Rs 100 each. The company would seek shareholders approval for the proposal through a postal ballot.																								 Dell has launched its Poweredge range of servers in India that can act as building blocks for large applications. The company has also launched Openmanage 4, a systems management software.																								 Union Bank of India has tied up with HCL for giving loans for computers. Other products launched by the bank include educational loans for students of ICFAI University, a bancassurance scheme with LIC, e-banking and mortgage.																								 RPG Life Sciences Limited has set itself the target of doubling exports in the current financial year from Rs 29 crore in 2003-04. The company said it has put enhanced focus on registration of drug master files and product dossiers in various markets to achieve the target.																								 Tata Tea Ltd has decided to close down its spices centre at Cochin as part of the plan to come out of non-core businesses even as it has developed a new instant tea product for the Japanese market. The company has decided to close down the spices centre at Cochin as the operations are not part of our core activity, Tata Tea said.																								 Bharat Heavy Electricals Ltds thermal generating sets produced 8 per cent more electricity at 109.5 billion units in April-July 2004 compared with 101.19 billion units in the year-ago period. The plant load factor of the thermal sets also improved to 75.6 per cent from 71.4 per cent in April-July 2003.																								 The listing of Mayajaal Entertainment Ltds shares on the stock market after the restructuring in Pentamedia Graphics will not result in the delisting of Pentamedias shares from the bourses. 																								 Anglo-Dutch oil giant Shell will begin auto fuel retailing in India by the end of 2004, Shell India chairman Vikram Singh Mehta said. Shell has a licence to set up 2000 petrol stations in the country and plans to set up the pumps in phases.																								 The Chennai-based Central Institute of Plastics Engineering and Technology (Cipet) has planned an investment of Rs 60 crore, which includes building an international faculty training centre, a hostel and staff quarters. ADVERTISEMENT
